# NextGit Project Rules

Firstly, BE INTERACTIVE. Do not spend excessive time thinking about things when you can simply ask the human.  The human is bored and wants to do something too, rather than leave you running for hours doing all the thinking.

## Project Overview

NextGit is a Glulx interpreter for the ZX Spectrum Next.

It is based on:

- Git (Glulx interpreter)
- A custom Glk implementation called NextGlk

## Structure

/docs - Documentation
/nextglk - Implementation
/tests - Tests
/thirdparty - Third-party code used as references. Do not inspect unless explicitly required.

## Building

Never use:

    make
    make clean

Always use the build scripts in the repository root.

Available scripts:

    rebuild-cheapglk.ps1

Builds:

    gitc

against CheapGlk.

Available scripts:

    rebuild-nextglk.ps1

Builds:

    gitn

against NextGlk.

CheapGlk exists for compatibility verification.

NextGlk is the production target.

The default Git Makefile configuration still targets CheapGlk.

## Architecture

Game
    ->
Git VM
    ->
Glk ABI
    ->
NextGlk
    ->
Spectrum Next Platform

Git must remain as close to upstream as possible.

Do not modify Git VM behaviour unless explicitly requested.

Prefer implementing missing functionality in NextGlk.

## CheapGlk Compatibility Policy

CheapGlk is the behavioural reference implementation.

When debugging:

    CheapGlk wins unless there is a proven reason not to.

Do not assume:

    "The specification probably means..."

when CheapGlk demonstrates actual behaviour.

The preferred debugging workflow is:

    Bug
        ->
    Run same scenario on CheapGlk
        ->
    Run same scenario on NextGlk
        ->
    Identify first behavioural divergence
        ->
    Create test
        ->
    Fix divergence
        ->
    Re-test

Do NOT begin with:

    architectural theories
    root-cause analysis
    speculative logging

Begin with:

    behavioural comparison

The key question is:

    "What does CheapGlk do?"

not:

    "What do we think should happen?"

## Platform

Target:

- ZX Spectrum Next
- z88dk
- NextZXOS
- SD card storage

Optional:

- Raspberry Pi acceleration

The interpreter must function without Raspberry Pi acceleration.

## Linux vs Spectrum Next Rules

ZX Spectrum Next behaviour is the target behaviour.

Linux exists to make Spectrum Next development and testing practical.

Linux and Spectrum Next must behave identically whenever possible.

If the Spectrum Next implementation requires a workaround:

    use the same workaround on Linux

unless there is a proven technical reason not to.

Do not introduce:

    Linux-only behaviour

Do not introduce:

    Spectrum-only behaviour

unless required by hardware limitations.

If a feature cannot realistically exist on the Spectrum Next:

    do not implement it on Linux.

Testing is only useful when both platforms behave the same.

## Glk

NextGlk is a genuine Glk implementation.

Do not create alternative abstraction layers.

Use:

- glk.h
- gi_dispa.c
- gi_dispa.h

as the ABI contract.

## Memory

Do not implement memory banking inside NextGlk.

Memory banking belongs to:

- VM memory manager
- Story memory subsystem

NextGlk owns:

- UI state
- Image cache
- Platform I/O

## Graphics

Games use:

- Inform 7
- Glulx
- Inline images

Current requirements:

- Inline image display
- No sound

Initial UI layout:

+----------------------+
|       IMAGE          |
+----------------------+
|      TEXT            |
|      TEXT            |
| >                    |
+----------------------+

## Coding Rules

Always provide:

- Complete files
- Complete functions

Never provide:

- Partial snippets
- Search-and-replace instructions
- "Insert here" guidance

When generating code:

- Compilable first
- Functional second

Stub implementations are acceptable if clearly marked.

## Development Strategy

1. ZX Spectrum Next is the target platform.
2. Linux exists only as a development platform.
3. Linux and Spectrum Next behaviour must remain identical whenever possible.
4. Behavioural compatibility is more important than architectural elegance.
5. CheapGlk is the behavioural reference implementation.
6. If CheapGlk and NextGlk behave differently, assume NextGlk is wrong until proven otherwise.
7. Prefer executable tests over theoretical analysis.
8. Prefer compatibility tests over extensive logging.
9. Prefer behavioural comparison over architectural reasoning.
10. Keep commits small.
11. Create tests for discovered divergences.
12. Fix divergences before investigating downstream symptoms.

## Investigation Rules

When debugging:

1. Reproduce the problem.
2. Run the same scenario on CheapGlk.
3. Run the same scenario on NextGlk.
4. Identify the first behavioural divergence.
5. Create a compatibility test.
6. Fix the divergence.
7. Re-test.

Do not spend extended periods investigating theories before locating a behavioural divergence.

Good investigation output:

    CheapGlk:
        X

    NextGlk:
        Y

    First divergence:
        Function Z

Bad investigation output:

    Maybe...
    Perhaps...
    Theoretically...
    We think...

Do not continue tracing once the first behavioural divergence has been identified.

Fix the divergence first.

Only continue if the problem remains.

## Documentation

Prefer:

    behavioural tests

before:

    root-cause analysis

Prefer:

    documentation

before:

    significant architectural changes

